    "documents": [
      {
        "id": "587e56d4-9014-43f6-9224-6e7af4fccaf6",
        "score": 0.4922493,
        "text": "The document outlines the process for assigning Capacity Accreditation Resource Classes to Installed Capacity Suppliers for the upcoming Capability Year by the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO). Key points include:\n\n1. **Assignment Notification**: NYISO will inform each supplier of their assigned class before the deadline in the ICAP Event Calendar.\n\n2. **Dispute Resolution**: If a supplier believes their assignment is incorrect, they must notify NYISO before the deadline. If unresolved, NYISO will assign a class for the year.\n\n3. **Supplier Responsibilities**: Suppliers must provide their class assignment to NYISO by the deadline.\n\n4. **Audit and Penalties**: NYISO may audit assignments. Inaccurate assignments can lead to penalties.\n\n5. **Finality of Assignments**: Assignments are final after the deadline. Late market entries will receive their class during registration.\n\n6. **Reference**: More details are available on the NYISO accreditation webpage.\n\nThe document emphasizes deadlines, accuracy, and the finality of assignments to ensure proper market operations.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual/page_249.jpg",
          "page_num": 249,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "2418dcc9-c47f-4f11-8e00-9e2963db9b4d",
        "score": 0.49158671,
        "text": "The document page discusses the uplift costs from guarantee payments in New York for the years 2016 and 2017. In 2017, the total uplift cost was $38 million, a 12% decrease from 2016's $43 million. The decline was mainly in Western New York, which saw a 49% reduction, and Long Island, with a 38% reduction. These reductions were due to less reliability commitment and out-of-market (OOM) dispatch. The local uplift in Western New York decreased significantly due to transmission upgrades and the expiration of the Milliken RSSA. The remaining local uplift could be eliminated if constraints were modeled in NYISO\u2019s day-ahead and real-time markets.\n\nAdditionally, the DAMAP, Min Oil Burn, and EDRP/SCR categories saw a reduction of over $5 million. Most uplift charges in 2016 occurred during high load days in July and August, which were not present in 2017 due to milder weather.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2017/page_109.jpg",
          "page_num": 109,
          "title": "2017 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2017,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "772cbe24-0adc-4841-a6aa-8927cd1c6c34",
        "score": 0.4878413,
        "text": "The document page from the New York ISO Installed Capacity Manual outlines procedures related to ICAP Demand Curves and supplemental supply fees:\n\n1. **FERC Filing of ICAP Demand Curves (5.6.7):** \n   - NYISO must file Board-approved ICAP Demand Curve parameters with FERC by November 30 before the first Capability Period in the review. This includes methodologies and inputs for annual updates for the remaining Capability Years.\n\n2. **Annual Updates of the ICAP Demand Curves (5.6.8):**\n   - NYISO will conduct annual updates for years 2-4 of the ICAP Demand Curves as per the NYISO Services Tariff. Results are presented to Market Participants, and updated values are posted by November 30 before the new Capability Year. These updates are accessible online.\n\n3. **Supplemental Supply Fee (5.7):**\n   - If a Load Serving Entity (LSE) fails to meet its capacity requirements after an ICAP Spot Market Auction, a supplemental supply fee is assessed. This fee is based on the Market-Clearing Price of Unforced Capacity. NYISO uses these fees to procure Unforced Capacity at or below the market-clearing price from qualified suppliers. Suppliers include those not previously qualified, those offering above market-clearing prices, and those not offering in the auction.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Installed_Capacity_Manual/page_229.jpg",
          "page_num": 229,
          "title": "Installed Capacity Manual",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "f555ba59-0aa3-494c-b50f-fbfc654d4f1f",
        "score": 0.48413533,
        "text": "The document discusses the process and results of the Class Year 2021 (CY21) study cycle related to deliverability and transmission planning for energy projects. It outlines the requirements for projects to pay for upgrades to receive Energy Resource Interconnection Service (ERIS) and Capacity Resource Interconnection Service (CRIS) rights. The study identifies necessary upgrades to ensure projects can deliver energy without violating transmission constraints.\n\nKey points include:\n\n- The Class Year Study helps developers decide whether to pay for required upgrades, receive ERIS or CRIS rights, or withdraw.\n- Recent studies have taken about two years, with increasing numbers of participants and costs.\n- CY21 began in February 2021 and concluded in January 2023, with participants requesting 11 GW of ERIS and 10 GW of CRIS.\n- The CY21 SUF Study identified over $900 million in required upgrades, with $800 million for direct project connections and $100 million for systemwide reliability.\n- Sixteen projects requesting 4 GW of CRIS were not fully deliverable, with less than 400 MW partially deliverable.\n- NYISO identified $1.5 billion in System Deliverability Upgrades (SDUs) for these projects, with costs ranging from $468 to $2,557 per kW of UCAP.\n- The document includes a table summarizing the results and costs of the CY21 SDU Study.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2023/page_46.jpg",
          "page_num": 46,
          "title": "2023 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2023,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "a7d43ff1-4d13-404c-8b4b-0d2edc71769d",
        "score": 0.4819264,
        "text": "The document discusses the reduction in total guarantee payment uplift costs, which fell by 32% from $77 million in 2018 to $52 million in 2019. This decrease was attributed to reduced supplemental commitments in New York City, lower gas prices, and decreased load levels during summer months. New York City accounted for $29 million (55%) of the BPCG in 2019, with over $21 million paid to generators for N-1-1 local requirements. Recommendations were made to adjust NYISO's local reserve requirements to improve efficiency. Long Island accounted for $15 million (28%) of BPCG, with nearly $10 million related to managing congestion and voltage needs. Recommendations were also made for modeling constraints in Long Island's markets.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2019/page_332.jpg",
          "page_num": 332,
          "title": "2019 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2019,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "aed2ded1-e2b3-4a2f-acb3-e6c8d23f1b07",
        "score": 0.48139572,
        "text": "The document page is from Section IV of a report detailing proposed projects in the Interconnection Facilities Study stage of the NYISO interconnection process. It includes information on re-ratings and deactivations of facilities. \n\n- **Table IV-1** lists proposed facilities that have completed, are enrolled in, or are candidates for the Class Year Interconnection Facilities Study.\n- **Table IV-2** reports units with proposed re-ratings, though none are applicable for this report.\n- **Tables IV-3, IV-4, and IV-5** list deactivated resources:\n  - **Table IV-3** shows deactivated units not listed in Existing Capacity Table III-2 with unexpired CRIS MW.\n  - **Table IV-4** shows units deactivated since the 2023 Gold Book.\n  - **Table IV-5** lists units with future deactivation notices.\n- **Table IV-6** lists potential generator status changes to comply with New York State rules and climate policy, including changes to simple-cycle combustion turbines and NYPA generators.\n- **Table IV-7** provides information on proposed large load projects in the NYISO Interconnection Queue.\n\nThe tables are current through March 15, 2024, with monthly updates available online.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Load_&_Capacity_Data/page_123.jpg",
          "page_num": 123,
          "title": "Load & Capacity Data",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "14a3f2e3-fafe-4901-874e-a94ec44c6355",
        "score": 0.48044667,
        "text": "This document page discusses deliverability and transmission planning related to the interconnection of energy projects, focusing on the categories of upgrades identified in the Cluster Study and Class Year process. The key points include:\n\n1. **Categories of Upgrades:**\n   - **Connecting Transmission Owner\u2019s Attachment Facilities (CTOAF):** Facilities required to connect a project to the transmission owner's network.\n   - **System Upgrade Facilities (SUF):** Network upgrades needed for projects to comply with NYISO\u2019s Minimum Interconnection Standard (MIS). Projects must pay allocated costs to receive the right to sell energy (ERIS). The MIS addresses reliability impacts but allows normal operating actions to avoid adverse effects.\n   - **System Deliverability Upgrades (SDU):** Upgrades required for resources to be deliverable under NYISO\u2019s Deliverability Interconnection Standard (DIS). Projects must pay for these upgrades to receive the right to sell capacity (CRIS). The DIS ensures that new and existing resources can deliver output without violating transmission constraints.\n\n2. **Process and Costs:**\n   - Developers must decide whether to pay for upgrades to receive ERIS or CRIS rights or withdraw from the study.\n   - The number of resources seeking interconnection and upgrade costs have increased recently.\n   - Class Year studies typically take about two years, while the Cluster Study aims for a 590-day timeline.\n   - New resources not part of an ongoing study must wait for a new study to begin.\n   - If SDUs are needed, a preliminary cost estimate is issued, and affected projects may enter an Additional SDU Study for final cost allocations.\n\n3. **Inefficient Upgrade Project Selection \u2013 Class Year 2023:**\n   - The most recent Class Year study (2023) started in January 2023 and finished in early 2025.\n   - Participants requested about 15 GW of ERIS and 14 GW of CRIS.\n   - The study identified $2.8 billion in CTOAF and SUF costs, with individual cost allocations ranging from $0 to $581 per kW of nameplate capacity, averaging $207 per kW.\n   - Proposed projects were generally fully deliverable except on Long Island, where an Additional SDU Study was necessary.\n\nThe page also includes references to additional details on the interconnection process and related study reports available on NYISO\u2019s website.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-chat-storage/NYISO/report/2024/page_50.jpg",
          "page_num": 50,
          "title": "2024 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2024,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "ba443407-65a6-4cc5-b29f-9f5c3c86bec3",
        "score": 0.47704127,
        "text": "The document page is from Section IV of a report detailing proposed projects in the Interconnection Facilities Study stage of the NYISO interconnection process. It includes information on re-ratings and deactivations:\n\n- **Table IV-1**: Lists proposed facilities that have completed, are enrolled in, or are candidates for the Class Year Interconnection Facilities Study, or have met other milestones.\n- **Table IV-2**: Reports units that have proposed re-ratings (none for this report).\n- **Tables IV-3, IV-4, IV-5**: List deactivated resources.\n  - **Table IV-3**: Shows deactivated units no longer in Existing Capacity Table III-2 with unexpired CRIS MW.\n  - **Table IV-4**: Lists units deactivated since the 2022 Gold Book.\n  - **Table IV-5**: Lists units with future deactivation notices.\n- **Table IV-6**: Lists proposed status changes of simple-cycle combustion turbines to comply with the DEC Peaker Rule.\n- **Table IV-7**: Provides information on proposed large load projects in the NYISO Interconnection Queue.\n\nThe data is current as of March 15, 2023, with updates available on the NYISO website.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Load_&_Capacity_Data/page_123.jpg",
          "page_num": 123,
          "title": "Load & Capacity Data",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "3aefb51d-3a99-4a81-b84b-aecd70e1458d",
        "score": 0.47538438,
        "text": "The document page is from Section IV of a report discussing proposed projects in the Interconnection Facilities Study stage of the NYISO interconnection process. It includes:\n\n- **Table IV-1**: Lists proposed facilities that are completed, enrolled, or candidates for a Class Year Interconnection Facilities Study, or have met other milestones.\n- **Table IV-2**: Reports units with proposed re-ratings.\n- **Table IV-3**: Shows deactivated units no longer listed in Existing Capacity Table III-2 with unexpired CRIS MW.\n- **Table IV-4**: Lists units still in Table III-2 but deactivated since the 2020 Gold Book.\n- **Table IV-5**: Lists units with a future deactivation notice.\n- **Table IV-6**: Lists proposed status changes of simple-cycle combustion turbines to comply with the DEC Peaker Rule.\n- **Table IV-7**: Provides information on proposed large load projects in the NYISO Interconnection Queue.\n\nThe tables are current as of March 15, 2022. Monthly updates are available on the NY Power System Information & Outlook page.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/protocol/Load_&_Capacity_Data/page_117.jpg",
          "page_num": 117,
          "title": "Load & Capacity Data",
          "year": "",
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "protocol"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "e265fb5b-5098-4f8a-8529-b45dfcab7939",
        "score": 0.47440153,
        "text": "The document page presents data on uplift costs from guarantee payments in New York, categorized by region and year (2018-2019). The chart shows costs in millions of dollars for New York City, Long Island, East Upstate, West Upstate, and Imports, with a total for each year. In 2019, the total was $52 million, down from $77 million in 2018. Long Island's costs remained stable at $15 million each year, with a significant portion (67%) attributed to high-cost peaking resources managing congestion and voltage needs. Recommendations include modeling specific constraints to improve market efficiency and reliability.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/NYISO/report/2019/page_125.jpg",
          "page_num": 125,
          "title": "2019 State of the Market Report for the New York ISO Markets",
          "year": 2019,
          "market": "NYISO",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "error": null,
  "metadata": {}
}

