        "score": 0.6823195,
        "text": "The document page discusses two main services related to Distributed Energy Resources (DER) in the context of the New York Independent System Operator (NYISO):\n\n### 3.1. Energy Resource Interconnection Service (ERIS) for DER\n- ERIS can be obtained through NYISO's standard Small Generator Interconnection Procedures (SGIP) for individual DERs.\n- DERs must accept cost responsibility for any necessary upgrades to address reliability issues from interconnection.\n- The ERIS value is documented in the Interconnection Agreement.\n- DERs studied through non-NYISO procedures can still obtain an \"ERIS-equivalent\" value.\n- Further details are available in NYISO's Transmission Expansion and Interconnection Manual and other guides.\n\n### 3.2. Capacity Resource Interconnection Service (CRIS) for DER\n- CRIS can be obtained via Attachment S of the Open Access Transmission Tariff (OATT) if DERs accept cost responsibility for required upgrades.\n- DERs of 2MW or less can obtain CRIS without a deliverability study.\n- Non-NYISO interconnected DERs must be studied for deliverability unless smaller than 2MW.\n- Demand Side Resources in the Capacity market do not need CRIS; their Installed Capacity (ICAP) is based on maximum output during a DMNC test.\n- For DER aggregations with energy duration limits, the maximum CRIS request is based on the minimum of expected maximum injection capability, nameplate capacity, or the sum of requested and existing ERIS.\n\nThe document provides references to various manuals and guides for more detailed information.",
